<li>    Peter C. Cramton, "Money Out of Thin Air: The Nationwide Narrowband PCS Auction," <I>Journal of Economics and Management Strategy</I>, Vol. 4, No. 2 (Summer 1995), p. 339.<p>
<li>    <I>Economic Report of the President</I> (Washington, D.C.: U.S. Government Printing Office, February 1996), p. 160.<p>
<li>    Edmund L. Andrews, "In Auctions of Airwaves, The Sky Seems to Be the Limit," <I>The New York Times</I>, February 26, 1996, p. D1.<p>
<li>    See <I>Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993</I>, Conference Report of the Committee on the Budget, U.S. House of Representatives, 103rd Congress, Report No. 103-213, August 4, 1993, p. 481.<p>
<li>    For more information, see Thierer and Barry, "How the Telecom Bill Gives Away $70 Billion in Family Tax Relief to the Broadcast Industry"; Adam D. Thierer, "The Great Taxpayer Rip-off of 1995," <I>Regulation</I>, No. 4 (1995), pp. 21-23; Thomas W. Hazlett, "Free the Airwaves," <I>The American Enterprise</I>, Vol. 7, No. 2 (March/April 1996), p. 71-72; Safire, "Stop the Giveaway"; Karen Kerrigan, "Hijacking the Broadcast Spectrum," <I>The Washington Times</I>, August 21, 1995, p. A18; "I-Way Detours," <I>The Wall Street Journal</I>, December 27, 1995, p. 10.<p>
<li>    Michael Schrage, "HDTV's Policy and Technology Aren't Tuned to the Same Wavelength," <I>The Washington Post</I>, April 14, 1995, p. B2.<p>
<li>    <I>Ibid.</I><p>
<li>    Thomas Hazlett, "Spectrum Auctions -- Only a First Step," <I>The Wall Street Journal</I>, December 20, 1994, p. A14.<p>
<li>    Coase, "The Federal Communications Commission," p. 18.<p>
<li>    Testimony of Peter K. Pitsch before the U.S. Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation, July 27, 1995, p. 3.<p>
<li>    <I>Ibid.</I><p>
<li>    Coase, "The Federal Communications Commission," pp. 8-9.<p>
<li>    See William T. Mayton, "The Illegitimacy of the Public Interest Standard at the FCC," <I>Emory Law Journal</I>, Vol. 38 (1989), pp. 715-769; Mark S. Fowler and Daniel L. Brenner, "A Marketplace Approach to Broadcast Deregulation," <I>Texas Law Review</I>, Vol. 60 (1982-1983), pp. 207-257; Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 173-174; Thierer, "A Report Card on the Pressler Telecommunications Plan (S. 652)," p. 14-15.<p>
<li>    This does not mean, however, that broadcasters put up a serious fight to end the public trustee paradigm. In fact, on one hand they speak of its importance to ensure that viable competitors are kept out of their market, while on the other they cite its intrusiveness as an excuse to produce mediocre programming. As Henry Geller, fellow at the Markle Foundation, notes, "A broadcaster loves to be considered a public interest figure. Broadcasters generally want the economic benefits of being a public fiduciary without having to meet the burden of adhering to public interest content regulation."  See Henry Geller, "Broadcasting and the Public Trustee Notion: A Failed Promise," <I>Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy</I>, Vol. 10, No. 1 (Winter 1987), p. 90.<p>
<li>    Federal Communications Commission, <I>Editorializing by Broadcast Licensees</I>, 13 F.C.C. 1246 (1949).<p>
<li>    For more information, see Adam D. Thierer, "Why the Fairness Doctrine is Anything But Fair," Heritage Foundation <I>Executive Memorandum</I> No. 368, October 29, 1993; E. Brandt Gustavson, "The Fairness Doctrine: Once and Future Threat to Speech, Religion," in <I>Speaking Freely: The Public Interest in Unfettered Speech</I> (Washington, D.C.: The Media Institute, 1995), pp. 87-106; "The Hush Rush Law," <I>The Wall Street Journal</I>, September 1, 1993, p. A14; John Corry, "Fairness Most Foul," <I>The American Spectator</I>, November 1993, pp. 50-51; Thomas W. Hazlett, "The Fairness Doctrine and the First Amendment," <I>The Public Interest</I>, Summer 1989, pp. 103-116; Jonathan W. Emord, "Toward a Free Broadcast Press," <I>Freedom, Technology, and the First Amendment</I> (San Francisco, Cal: Pacific Research Institute, 1991), pp. 233-248; Krattenmaker and Powe, "The Fairness Doctrine," in <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 237-275; Ford Rowan, <I>Broadcast Fairness: Doctrine, Practice, Prospects</I> (New York: Longman, 1984).<p>
<li>    For more information, see Adam D. Thierer, "Who Will Mind the Children?  The Regulation of Children's Programming in the Information Age," in <I>Speaking Freely: The Public Interest in Unfettered Speech</I> (Washington, D.C.: The Media Institute, 1995), pp. 47-66.<P>
<li>    United States Constitution, Amendment 1.<p>
<li>    Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, p. 18.<p>
<li>    For a more detailed discussion of this dual system of regulation, see <I>Print and Electronic Media: The Case for First Amendment Parity</I>, Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation, 98th Congress, 1st Session Committee Print, May 3, 1983; Jonathan W. Emord, <I>Freedom, Technology, and the First Amendment</I> (San Francisco, Cal: Pacific Research Institute, 1991); Matthew L. Spitzer, "The Constitutionality of Licensing Broadcasters," <I>New York University Law Review</I> Vol. 64 (1989), p. 990; John Thorne, Peter W. Huber, and Michael K. Kellogg, "Free Speech," in <I>Federal Broadband Law</I> (Little, Brown & Co., forthcoming); Krattenmaker and Powe, "Broadcasting Versus Print," in <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 203-236; Harry Kalven, Jr., "Broadcasting, Public Policy and the First Amendment," <I>The Journal of Law and Economics</I>, Vol. 10 (October 1967), pp. 15-49.<p>
<li>    Timothy Dyk, "Full First Amendment Freedom for Broadcasters: The Industry as Eliza on the Ice and Congress as the Friendly Overseer," <I>Yale Journal of Regulation</I> Vol. 5 (1988), pp. 299, 308.<p>
<li>    See <I>Miami Herald Publishing Company v. Tornillo</I>, 418 U.S. 241 (1974); <I>Pacific Gas & Electric Company v. Public Utilities Commission</I>, 475 U.S. 1 (1986); <I>Near v. Minnesota</I>, 283 U.S. 697 (1931).<p>
<li>    Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, p. 235.<p>
<li>    See generally Robert Corn-Revere, "Who Speaks for the First Amendment: Why the FCC Should Look Before It Leaps on Children's TV," <I>Broadcasting & Cable</I>, June 27, 1994, p. 19; Robert Corn-Revere, "Television Violence and the Limits of Voluntarism," <I>Yale Journal of Regulation</I>, Vol. 12, No. 1 (Winter 1995), p. 205.<p>
<li>    Bruce Fein, "First Class First Amendment Rights for Broadcasters," <I>Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy</I>, Vol. 10, No. 1 (Winter 1987), p. 84.<p>
<li>    See NBC v. United States, 319 U.S. 190 (1943); <I>Red Lion Broadcasting Co. v. FCC</I>, 395 U.S. 367 (1969). <p>
<li>    See Fred H. Cate, "The First Amendment and the National Information Infrastructure," <I>Wake Forest Law Review</I>, Vol. 30, No. 1 (Spring 1995), pp. 37-40; Krattenmaker and Powe, <I>Regulating Broadcast Programming</I>, pp. 204-205.<p>
<li>    While granting property rights may seem like nothing more than a natural extension of providing full flexibility in use, an important difference exists. Full flexibility could be granted to spectrum users while they continue to lease their allocation from the federal government. While this system would be vastly more efficient than the current system, the federal government would still own the resource and would merely be granting licenses for a given period. Therefore, bureaucratic meddling could remain a serious problem, especially with regard to content regulation.<p>
<li>    The NTIA, which sits in the Department of Commerce, manages all federal government spectrum, such as that used for air traffic control, law enforcement, and especially military concerns.<p>
<li>    See generally, <I>The Telecom Revolution: An American Opportunity</I>, p. 70-79.
</ol><p>
