<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 2 footnotes</h3>
<P>



<P><B><A HREF="chpt2.html">Return to Chapter 2</A></B></P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="1">1</A></B></TT>	The 2.9 percent Medicare tax, as
explained above, applies to all income. The 12.4  percent Social Security tax,
however, applies only  to the first $61,600 of income (the reason being that
Social Security is somewhat akin to  an insurance premium; taxing additional
income would have the effect of boosting the  retirement benefits of those who
had higher  incomes during their working years).
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="2">2</A></B></TT>	This section is derived largely 
(though updated) from Robert Rector, &quot;How to  Strengthen America's
Crumbling Families,&quot; Heritage  Foundation <CITE><U>Backgrounder</U></CITE>
No. 894, April 28, 1992.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="3">3</A></B></TT>	Liberal and conservative economists 
agree that both shares of the Social Security tax  are in fact taxes on workers'
wages. See Joseph A. Pechman and Benjamin A. Okner, 
<U><CITE>Who Bears the Tax Burden?</CITE></U>  (Washington, D.C.: The 
Brookings Institution, 1974), pp. 2543.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="4">4</A></B></TT>	Data from the U.S. Bureau of the 
Census. Total pretax income includes the employer  share of Social Security tax
deducted from the  worker's wages. In this case, the median income for  a family
of four in 1994 is $47,012. Adding $3,596 from the employer's share of payroll 
taxes brings the gross family income to $56,608. 
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="5">5</A></B></TT>	<U><CITE>1994 Annual Report of the
Board of  Trustees of the Federal OldAge and Survivors Insurance and Disability
Insurance Trust  Funds</CITE></U>, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  April 12, 1994.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="6">6</A></B></TT>	This is not to suggest that 
politicians should be given power to invest the funds.  Such a policy inevitably
would result in political manipulation, as surplus funds would be  steered to
politically wellconnected industries  and used to bail out businesses in the
states and districts of senior lawmakers.  A governmentcontrolled retirement
system, by definition, must be operated on a  payasyougo basis.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="7">7</A></B></TT> The chart shows a decline in tax 
collections in the early 1980s, but this occurred  as a result of the 19811982
recession (which started, incidentally, before Reagan's  first fiscal year
began). Moreover, this decline  in revenue also took place before there was a
tax cut. The Reagan economic package was  approved in the summer of 1981, but
the tax cut  was phased in over several years and not fully implemented until
1985. The tax burden  actually rose in Reagan's first year in office, as the
minor tax cut in 1981 was overwhelmed  by previously legislated payroll tax
increases and inflationinduced bracket creep  (indexing to protect taxpayers
from inflation did not  go into effect until 1985). The 1982 portion of the tax
cut was more significant, but it  was roughly canceled out by bracket creep and
payroll tax changes.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="8">8</A></B></TT>	The Administration's $300perchild 
credit begins phasing out for families with  incomes above $60,000 and reaches
zero at $75,000  in family income. The credit increases in value to $500 per
child after 1998.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="9">9</A></B></TT>	For taxpayers filing jointly with 
incomes above $110,000, the credit phases out at a  rate of $25 for each $1,000
above the threshold (a range of $20,000), thus fully phasing out  at $130,000 in
income. For families with two children, the two credits are phased out fully  at
$150,000 in income. For single filers, the credit begins to phase out at $75,000
in  income.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="10">10</A></B></TT>	Clinton's 1997 budget has modified 
this provision, thus making more families eligible for his $300 tax credit.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="11">11</A></B></TT> U.S. House of Representatives, 
<U><CITE>Balanced Budget Act of 1995: Conference Report to  Accompany H.R.
2491</CITE></U>, Report 104350, pp. 13211323.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="12">12</A></TT></B><U>	<CITE>Ibid</CITE></U>., p. 1355.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="13">13</A></B></TT>	These are 1995 dollar figures using 
the Laurence H. Meyer and Associates macroeconomic model of the United States
economy.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="14">14</A></TT></B>	This also means that income should 
be defined properly. Provisions which force taxpayers to overstate their income,
such as  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  alternative minimum tax, would be
repealed. Nor should taxpayers be forced to  undercount business expenses. As a
result,  &quot;depreciation&quot; would be replaced by expensing.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="15">15</A></TT></B>	Taxation is not the only government 
activity that inflates the cost of hiring workers and reduces takehome pay.
Myriad  regulations, mandated benefits, unemployment  compensation, liability
costs, and labor laws  drive up the cost of employment and shrink  workers' pay.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="16">16</A></TT></B>	This process usually works by 
delaying, reducing, or canceling wage increases. In  most years, additional
investment and training increase worker productivity, making  employees more
valuable and allowing businesses to  increases wages. When these productivity
increases are accompanied by higher taxes, however,  it is government, not the
workers, that captures all the benefits.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="17">17</A></TT></B>	U.S. Treasury Department memorandum, 
&quot;An Analysis of a Flat Rate Consumption Tax,&quot;  undated.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="18">18</A></TT></B>	News release, &quot;The Fate of Flat
Tax  Critics,&quot; Office of Representative Richard K.  Armey, December 8,
1994.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="19">19</A></TT></B>	David Wessel, &quot;Another Round:
Talk of  Tax Reform is Gaining Momentum, But Plans Vary 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  Widely,&quot; The Wall Street
Journal, January 31, 1995.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="20">20</A></TT></B>	In its analysis of the Armey 
proposal, the Treasury Department admitted that &quot;no  attempt is made to
estimate the taxinduced behavioral responses of either individuals  or
corporations. Following the standard revenue estimating conventions used by both
the  Office of Tax Analysis and the Joint Committee on Taxation, the
macroeconomic aggregates,  such as the level of compensation, prices,
employment, and gross domestic product, have  been assumed to be unchanged by
the proposal.&quot;
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="21">21</A></TT></B>	Using $7 trillion as an estimate of 
1995 nominal GDP. The calculations compare GDP  with 5.5 percent nominal growth
to GDP with 6 percent nominal growth (assuming a similar  inflation rate).
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="22">22</A></TT></B>	Assuming taxes would take only 15 
percent of the added output. Since taxes currently consume about 19 percent of
GDP, this  estimate understates the potential supplyside  impact on revenues.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="23">23</A></TT></B>	In economic and financial circles, 
this concept is known as present value.
</P>
<P><B><TT><A NAME="24">24</A></TT></B>	Conversation with author and 
