<html>
<title>Russell Kirk Lectures</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<hr size=3 width=50%><br>
<H2>The Russell Kirk Memorial Lectures<br>
 1996 Schedule</h2><br>

<h3><i>"Recovering the Permanent Things"</i></h3></center><br>

<i>The Russell Kirk Memorial Lecture Series consists of four major lectures a year -- primarily by scholars -- on what Dr. Kirk called the permanent things: community, religion, knowledge, literature, history, virtue, and family.</i><p>

<i>Putting the Self Into Self Interest: An Economist Looks At Values</i><br>
Wednesday, October 2, 1996<br>
<b>Dr. Jennifer Roback Morse </b><br>
Associate Professor of Economics, George Mason University
<p>
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect571.html"><i>Is the Land of the Free Still the Home of the Brave?</i></a> <br>
Wednesday, May 15<br>
 <b>James Muller</b><br>
 Professor, Political Science, University of Alaska.
<p>

<a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect570.html"><i>Eve Without Adam: What Genesis Has To Tell America About Natural Law</i></a><br>
Wednesday, May 1<br>
<b>David Forte</b><br>
Professor of Law<br>
Cleveland-Marshall College of Law, Cleveland State University
<p>
<center><h2>1995 Lectures</h2></center>

<i><a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/lect543.html">First Principles in the Political Arena</a></i><br>
Tuesday, September 26<br>
<b>The Honorable John Engler</b><br>
Governor of Michigan<br>
<p>
<i><a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/lect545.html">Homer, Shakespeare and Tolstoy: What Literature Teaches About the Collapse and Recovery of the Family</a></i><br>
Thursday, October 19<br>
<b>David Patterson</b><br>
Associate Professor of European Literature<br>
Oklahoma State University<br>
<p>
<i><a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect547.html">The Conservative Heart: Life  With Russell Kirk</a></i><br>
Friday, November 17<br>
<b>Annette Kirk</b>
<p>
<i><a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/lect550.html">The Mystic Cords of Memory: Reclaiming America's History</a></i><br>
Wednesday, December 13<br>
<b>Wilfred McClay</b><br>
Associate Professor of History<br>
Tulane University<br>
<p>
<center>

<hr>
<h3>Russell Amos Kirk</h3><br>
<b>1918-1994</b><br></center>
<p>
"For more than forty years, Russell Kirk was the conscience of the conservative movement. As a scholar, essayist, lecturer, and critic, he saw contemporary political events against the backdrop of history, philosophy, and literature -- subjects in which his background was astonishingly thorough. Following the publication of his masterful <I>The Conservative Mind</i>, Dr. Kirk watched the conservative intellectual revival develop around him until his solitary cause of the early 1950s became the dominant trend of the 1980s. As much as any other living American, Russell Kirk was responsible for the growth of that movement. His works have given the conservative movement sage guidance in its efforts to redeem the time and champion the permanent things."
<p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin J. Feulner, Jr.</a>
<p><p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif
" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
