<TITLE>The Record on Foreign Policy and Defense -- Issues '96 -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3Introduction</H3>
<P>

<CENTER><H2>
THE RECORD ON FOREIGN POLICY AND DEFENSE
</H2>


<CITE>By <a href="/heritage/staff/holmes.htm">Kim R. Holmes</a>
</CITE>
</center><P>

<B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration came into office with a widely  recognized lack
of experience in defense and foreign policy. But  the new President did not take
the necessary steps to correct this  deficiency. The new Commander in Chief,
already suspect in the  national security community for his history of draft
avoidance  during the Vietnam War, made decisions which reinforced his image as 
a President out of touch with the military services and inattentive  to foreign
policy and national security issues. His flip-flops on  Haiti, Cuba, China, and
Bosnia weakened American credibility  abroad and created doubts around the world
about U.S. leadership.  Moreover, the Clinton Administration has presided over a period of neglect  and decline of
U.S. military strength. The Administration's series  of missteps amounts to
little more than on-the-job-training.  Despite over three years in office, the
job as leader and chief architect  of America's foreign and defense policies
still appears to be too  big for Bill Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Instead of developing a clear and coherent foreign and  defense policy
grounded in American principles and national interest,  the Clinton
Administration allowed politics and indifference to  foreign policy issues to
create muddle and confusion in America's  foreign 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  policy. Until the beginning of the
104th Congress and the  Contract With America, Congress regrettably did little
to correct the  unwise course being followed by the Administration. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The President and his advisors, indelibly influenced by their  opposition to
the Vietnam War, came into office confused about  the principles that legitimize
the exercise of American power. It  soon became apparent that the Clinton team
believed unilateral  U.S. action was improper, and that U.S. power must be  &quot;legitimized&quot;
by operating through some international or multilateral agency  like the United
Nations. The resulting policy of  &quot;assertive multilateralism&quot;
subordinated clear national interests to the  U.N. and other supranational
entities. Extending his liberal  worldview to international politics, President
Clinton in Somalia, Haiti,  and Bosnia looked upon foreign policy as social
work. Clinton's  vague global utopianism led him to commit the U.S. to dubious 
enterprises, with American soldiers needlessly killed and scarce  defense
dollars wasted. The Administration claims to have learned  that &quot;assertive
multilateralism&quot; in the U.N. does not work, but  the President exercised
the same unwise judgment from his early  years in office by unnecessarily and
unwisely sending U.S. troops  to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Dubious Foreign Policy Successes</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many of these enterprises have been hailed as foreign policy  successes by
the Clinton Administration. The President has  claimed that his greatest
successes are in North Korea, Haiti, and  Bosnia. But these claims are
overblown. For example, the  Administration has:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Made extraordinary concessions to a most dangerous 
potential enemy, North Korea.</B> Rewarding North Korea's blatant and 
persistent refusal to live up to its obligations as a signatory to  the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, the U.S. agreed to provide  $5 billion in fuel oil and
to help finance and build two new light  water reactors for Pyongyang. These
terms were spelled out in  the Nuclear Framework Agreement the Clinton
Administration  negotiated with North Korea. The Administration brags that this 
agreement gives the U.N.'s International Atomic Energy  Agency (IAEA) the right
to inspect certain nuclear facilities inside  North Korea. But the IAEA already
had the right to carry out  inspections. Moreover, the Nuclear Framework
Agreement provides no  guarantee that the North has stopped trying to build
nuclear weapons  at hidden sites, or that the North will continue to cooperate
with  the IAEA once Pyongyang has extracted financial and diplomatic 
concessions from the West.<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> North Korea has  been paid to do what
it already was obligated to do under the  Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, and
the U.S. is still not certain  that North Korea has stopped its nuclear weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Embarked on a costly venture of dubious value in Haiti.  President
Clinton hails his Haiti venture as a great foreign policy success.</B>  To be
sure, the U.S., the world's remaining military superpower,  did subdue the
Hemisphere's poorest and most backward country.  But for what purpose?  To
restore to office an avowed Marxist  demagogue known for his hostility to the
U.S. While the Haiti  mission did not turn into a Somalia-like disaster with the
loss of  American lives, it has cost upwards of $2 billion and placed enormous 
strain on U.S. forces at a time when they were engaged in many other  so-called
peace operations. Moreover, under the watchful eyes  of U.S. occupation forces,
former President Jean-Bertrand  Aristide 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  hijacked democracy in Haiti,
placing his hand-picked and  easily controlled successor in power via the
elections of December,  1995, and allowing political murders of his opponents to
occur  unpunished. <br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> The U.S. operation in Haiti was  unnecessary
and wasteful, serving no vital U.S. interest, and it did  not achieve its stated
purpose  the creation of democracy in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Boxed America into an unwise and unnecessary U.N. troop  commitment to
Bosnia.</B> By failing to lift the arms embargo on the  embattled Bosnians so
they could defend themselves, it was left up  to the Croatians to push back the
Bosnian Serbs, who had  dominated the military balance of power inside Bosnia.
Once this shift in  the balance of power occurred, the stage was set for the
peace  agreement which was negotiated November 30, 1995, in Dayton,  Ohio.
Although U.S. pressure and NATO airstrikes played a role  in bringing about the
Dayton agreement, the real key was the  military defeats which the Bosnians and
Croatians imposed on the  Bosnian Serbs last year. But because the Bosnian
Muslims do not fully  trust the Croatians  indeed a few years ago they were at
war with  each other  the Dayton peace agreement is not only very fragile,  it
requires the presence of 20,000 U.S. troops and other  NATO forces to enforce
it. Thus, by failing to lift the arms embargo  on Bosnia, President Clinton
practically guaranteed that U.S.  troops would have to go to Bosnia to enforce
the peace, something  which he had repeatedly in the past promised he would not
do.
<br>
<b>The  Bottom Line:</b> The U.S. troop deployment was unneccessary and  unwise, and
peace is by no means assured in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Claimed credit for the two Israeli-Palestinian peace accords  signed at
the White House in September 1993 and September 1995.</B>  But the two
agreements came about through bilateral negotiations  be
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  tween Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization,  initially conducted without the Administration's
knowledge. <br>
<b>The  Bottom Line:</b> President Clinton enjoyed two photo opportunities,
but  the diplomatic breakthroughs that produced the agreements  came about
mainly through bilateral talks between Israelis and  Palestinians, not through
American diplomatic efforts.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Claims to have advanced the peace process between the  Irish Catholic
minority in Northern Ireland and the Irish Protestant  majority, backed by the
British government.</B> But the  Administration's controversial embrace of Gerry
Adams, leader of Sinn Fein,  the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), is a risky  diplomatic gambit that has backfired. Despite the fact that
the  IRA has killed almost 2,000 people in terrorist attacks over the last  25
years, the Administration has rewarded it with a &quot;carrot and  carrot&quot;
policy. Clinton overruled the advice of his own State  Department, Defense
Department, and Justice Department to  allow Adams to obtain a visa to visit the
U.S. in February 1994.  In March 1995, the Administration allowed Adams to
travel to  the U.S. on a fund-raising trip, open an office in Washington, and 
visit the White House on Saint Patrick's Day. Although the IRA  agreed to a
cease-fire in its terrorist war, it did not agree to disarm,  and maintains a
huge arsenal, including more than a ton of  Semtex plastic explosive, much of it
provided by Libyan  dictator Muammar Qadhafi. Of course, the IRA broke its
cease-fire,  renewing its terrorist campaign, making a mockery of Clinton's 
efforts to bring peace to Nothern Ireland. <br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b>  Clinton's opportunistic embrace of Gerry Adams, motivated at least in  part by domestic
politics, has undermined U.S. counterterrorism  policy; strained relations with
Britain, a staunch ally; and raised the  IRA's expectations that Washington will
press London to make  conces
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  sions without IRA concessions,
thereby undermining the  chances of a genuine peace.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>NAFTA and GATT: Successes Unfulfilled</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One genuine success for which the Clinton Administration fails  to claim
much credit is the approval of the North American  Free Trade Agreement and the
Uruguay Round of talks in the  General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or GATT.
The Clinton  Administration is to be commended for completing these agreements, 
but the initiative and much of the work behind them occurred in  the Reagan and
Bush Administrations. Moreover, by dropping the  ball on expanding NAFTA to
include Chile, the Clinton  Administration has practically taken the U.S. out of
the game of expanding  free trade in the Western Hemisphere. As a result, the
President  has ceded the initiative to Brazil and others who may want to  create
trade blocs closed to the U.S. but possibly more open to U.S.  competitors in
Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Clinton's Failures</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While the President's foreign policy &quot;successes&quot; have proven to 
be doubtful, his many foreign policy failures are obvious and  admitted even by
his supporters. For example, the President has: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Dragged his feet on protecting the U.S. homeland and troops
 and interests abroad from the growing danger of ballistic missiles. </B> He cut
the budget for missile defense by over 50 percent from  levels projected by the
Bush Administration and has attempted  illegally to broaden the restrictions of
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic  Missile (ABM) Treaty, which imposes severe restrictions
on strategic  de
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  fenses, to cover tactical and
theater defenses as well. <br>
<b>The  Bottom Line:</b> Americans will be left vulnerable to
nuclear attack,  even though the Clinton Administration itself has admitted that
the  proliferation of nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles is the most 
serious threat to national security.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Wasted American lives and treasure on dubious peacekeeping  operations.</B>
Clinton allowed a limited, humanitarian mission to  Somalia to escalate into an
uncertain and dangerous  &quot;nation-building&quot; mission, which included
hunting Somali warlords and  disarming militant factions  in effect making the
U.S. a combatant in  a bloody civil war. Putting U.S. troops under a confused
U.N.  command structure, the Clinton Administration failed to provide  adequate
weapons and equipment to U.S. forces engaged in a  combat operation. The result
was an intense street battle in Mogadishu  in October 1993 which left 18 young
American Rangers dead,  75 other soldiers wounded and led to America's
humiliating  retreat from Somalia. <br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> American lives were lost 
unnecessarily, and U.S. national prestige and credibility suffered  needlessly.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Frittered away American military strength and credibility in a  series
of &quot;peace operations&quot; with little or no benefit to the  nation's
security, consuming billions of defense budget dollars intended  for training,
operations, and maintenance of U.S. forces and  equipment.</B> These missions
included an unwise expansion of the  peace mission in Somalia, which led to the
mission's failure, and  the dispatch of troops to peacekeeping missions in
Haiti,  Macedonia, and Bosnia. At the same time, by cutting the defense budget, 
the President has neglected the core duty of the armed forces: to  fight and win
wars in defense of U.S. strategic interests and  existing 
 military alliance commitments. 
<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Under  Clinton, American fighting troops are weaker and less able
to deal  with larger military contingencies, such as in Korea or the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Built America's military strategy on a potentially fatal illusion.  In
1993 President Clinton's Pentagon released a study of  America's long-range
military requirements.</B> Called the &quot;Bottom-Up  Review,&quot; this study
concluded that the U.S. should have the  means and forces to fight two nearly
simultaneous medium-sized  conflicts. Yet Clinton proceeded to cut the very
forces needed to  sustain this capability. The President refused to fund
adequately  and field the force which his own planners said the country  needed.
<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Because the U.S. will not be able to protect  all its interests
around the world, its alliances may weaken, its  credibility and influence may
wane, and Americans could be forced  to follow the lead of others rather than to
lead themselves.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Weakened the armed forces with social experimentation and  &quot;political
correctness.&quot;</B>  The President has imposed his radical  vision on the
military services by pushing women into combat  positions before their
effectiveness has been tested, or their impact on  combat effectiveness honestly
evaluated. He has advocated the  admission of acknowledged homosexuals into the
ranks, contrary to  the judgment of the nation's top military leaders. The
result has been  a corrosion of the mutual trust between leaders and those they 
lead that is essential to unit cohesion and combat  effectiveness.<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Clinton has weakened the morale of  America's fighting forces.
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>Followed a &quot;Russia-only&quot; policy that has not bolstered 
democracy in Russia, but it has blocked development of strong relations  with 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  former Soviet states like Ukraine.</B>
President Clinton has  staked U.S. policy on the fate of one man, President
Boris Yeltsin.  The ostensible reason for this policy is to bolster democracy in
 Russia, but it clearly has not worked. Yeltsin has kicked democrats  like
former Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev and former  Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly
Chubais out of his cabinet, replacing  them with old Soviet hardliners like
Yevgeny Primakov, the new  Foreign Minister. But still the U.S. offers Yeltsin
good will and  cooperation. Clinton has largely turned a blind eye to Russia's 
hard-line policy toward its former &quot;republics&quot; and provinces  the 
so-called &quot;Near Abroad&quot;  and he has failed to condemn Russian 
aggression in trouble spots like Chechnya, Moldova, and Georgia. 
<br>
<b>The  Bottom Line:</b> Clinton's policy of accommodation has not  worked. Russia continues to
drift away from democracy and toward a  more hard line foreign policy, while the
U.S. continues to offer  friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Put at risk key alliance relationships with Japan and the  Republic of
Korea. The Administration's effort last year to manage  trade with Japan was
acrimonious and counterproductive from the  start.</B> The U.S. reached auto
trade agreements with Japan in  November 1994 and March 1995, but these achieved
little and strained  U.S.-Japan relations. After initially denying that its
confrontational  policies were damaging the U.S.-Japan alliance, the 
Administration, under the Pentagon's leadership, belatedly tried to limit the 
damage and reaffirm the alliance. The main purpose of the April  1996
U.S.-Japanese summit is to repair the damage caused by the  previous year's
trade battles. At the same time, Clinton's efforts  to strike a nuclear bargain
with North Korea marginalized the  influence and role of a reliable U.S. ally,
South Korea. Recent  opinion polls by the United States Information Agency show
South  Korean 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  support for a U.S. military
presence at 72 percent, down 10  percent from 1994. Overall opinion of the U.S.
not only is down 20  percent, but also  and for the first time in 12 years  is
more  unfavorable (53 percent) than favorable (43 percent).<br><b>The Bottom  Line:</b> America's alliances with South Korea and Japan, key links in  the security chain
of Asia, have been weakened. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Damaged U.S. credibility in dealing with the People's Republic  of
China. After campaigning in 1992 to link China's Most  Favored Nation (MFN)
trading status to its human rights record,  President Clinton reversed himself
in 1994 and delinked MFN from  human rights.</B> <TT><B><A
HREF="ftntfor.htm#1">1</A></B></TT>  This was the correct
decision. As the Administration  belatedly recognized, the best way to encourage
China to  observe international norms of conduct is to promote policies which 
enhance economic interaction and, in turn, economic freedom  and reform. These
are the seeds from which democracy can  grow. However, the Administration's
flip-flops created the impression  of ineptness and weakness. <br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b>
While the  Administration ultimately did the right thing, its ill-conceived
linkage  policy cost the U.S. credibility both in Beijing and across Asia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Allowed Beijing to set America's agenda with the Republic  of China on
Taiwan.</B> In response to nearly unanimous  congressional resolutions, the
Administration relented and allowed  Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui to make a
&quot;private&quot; visit to his alma  mater, Cornell University, in June 1995.
Previously, in the face  of Beijing's protests, the Administration had resisted
the visit  of President Lee, claiming that it would violate its  &quot;One-China&quot;
policy. Clinton reversed himself only when he was pressured to  do so. The
mistake was the initial refusal to allow President Lee  to visit the U.S. 
<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Beijing should not be allowed  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  dictate the terms of America's &quot;unofficial&quot;
commercial and  cultural relations with Taiwan, and its interest in Taiwan's
security,  as established by the Taiwan Relations Act of 1979.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Abandoned three decades of principled U.S. policy towards  Cuba.</B>
President Clinton secretly negotiated with Fidel Castro's  communist regime in
August 1994 to reach an agreement whereby all  Cuban boat people intercepted at
sea by U.S. ships would be  repatriated forcibly to Cuba. Hitherto Cuban
refugees were permitted  to enter the U.S. without restriction.
<br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Clinton changed the longstanding U.S. policy of isolating communist  Cuba to a
new conciliatory stance, without winning any democratic  or free-market
concessions from Castro. Clinton was  eventually forced to abandon this
conciliatory policy, and to strengthen  the embargo against Cuba, but only after
he was forced to do so in  the aftermath of the Cuban downing of two U.S.
civilian aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Failed to take seriously the global challenge of radical or 
revolutionary Islam.</B> Nor has the President pursued realistic steps to  deal
with the Islamist threat to friendly regimes or secular Muslim  powers in the
Middle East, North Africa, and Central Asia. Instead,  he has sought to
establish diplomatic contacts with radical  Islamic movements such as Algeria's
Islamic Salvation Front, thereby  undermining secular regimes battling Islamic
radicals. As a  result, the U.S. is not properly anticipating the potential
realignment  of global power in regions critical to U.S. interests. <br>
<b>The Bottom Line:</b> Radical regimes could threaten not only U.S. access to oil, but  also
American lives and interests through terrorism.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The mistakes, misjudgments, and missed opportunities that  have
characterized the Clinton Administration's approach to foreign  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  defense policy over the past four
years are serious. They  have weakened U.S. influence and credibility abroad
and, unless  rectified, could lead inevitably to America's decline as a great 
power capable of defending its values and interests. For America, it  is either
lead or be led. The first road leads to freedom, security,  and greatness, the
second to weakness and submission. For its  own well-being, and for that of the
entire globe, America's  leadership needs to be restored.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The weak record of the Clinton Administration in foreign and  defense policy
was singled out for criticism in the GOP's  Contract With America. Alarmed over
Clinton's defense budget cuts  and failure to move rapidly toward a national
missile defense  system, Republicans marching under the banner of the Contract 
promised to restore America's military strength. Once elected in  November 1994,
they got to work on trying to fulfill their promise. On  February 7, 1995, the
House of Representatives passed the National  Security Revitalization Act (H.R.
7), which sought to establish  a commission to eliminate the funding shortfall
in defense, set a  new policy for the development and deployment of missile 
defenses, expand NATO membership, and limit the authority of the  President to
subordinate U.S. troops to United Nations command.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Senate did not take up H.R. 7. However, parts of H.R. 7  found their way
into different pieces of legislation in the Senate, such  as in the defense
authorization bill and foreign relations  authorization bill. While not all of
the original Contract items were included  in final legislation reconciling
differences between the House  and Senate  for example, Congress dropped the
House's demand  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  create a commission to examine
U.S. national security strategy   conservative supporters of the Contract
delivered on the  majority of their promises to the American people. 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>The Congress undertook a number of other foreign and  defense policy
initiatives in 1995 that complemented and supplemented  the legislation inspired
by the Contract With America. For  example, the new majority in Congress
endeavored to:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Restore America's military strength. Congress approved a 
defense spending bill that added $7 billion to the defense budget  request
submitted by President Clinton.</B> This money was needed not  only to keep
America's armed forces trained and combat ready, but  also to maintain a force
with modern high-technology weapons in  the 21st century. Primarily because he
counted on congressional  support for his Bosnia mission, President Clinton
bowed to  congressional demands and signed the defense appropriations bill for 
fiscal 1996, which provided the additional $7 billion above his  original
request. But in an unprecedented act the President vetoed  the accompanying
fiscal year 1996 defense authorization bill  which would have: 1) provided more
funds to maintain the  technological superiority of U.S. forces, 2) authorized a
pay raise and  housing allowance increase for military personnel (including
those  deployed to Bosnia), and 3) mandated the defense of the U.S.  homeland
against ballistic missiles. However, in early 1996 the  President signed a
different version of the defense authorization bill  that weakened missile
defense.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Move the United States closer to a national missile defense  system.</B>
The defense authorization bill approved by Congress but  vetoed by the President
sought to establish a clear timetable for  de
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  velopment and deployment of both
national and theater  missile defenses. Further, it sought to bar the
application of  Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty restrictions to theater
defense  systems. However, the President refused to sign the defense bill,
giving  as his primary reason the strong missile defense provisions it 
contained. Of course, the President eventually got his way,  forcing Congress to
accept a weakening of missile defense in the  final 1996 defense authorization
bill. Once again the President has  succeeded in blocking this country's ability
to defend its citizens  from nuclear attack and Congress was not able to muster
enough  votes to override his veto. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cut foreign aid.</B> While the new Republican majority promised 
extensive cuts in foreign aid, little has transpired by way of  revamping
America's wasteful foreign aid programs. Federal spending  on foreign aid will
likely be only $2 billion less in FY 1996 than  it was in FY 1995. However,
under the umbrella of a balanced  budget by the year 2002, further cuts are
likely. While current  cuts amount to nearly 30 percent for all programs except
aid to  Israel and Egypt, much still needs to be done. One step in the right 
direction is a new law, that the U.S. government report on the  progress being
made by foreign aid recipients developing free markets,  the main engine of
economic development. This effort was inspired  by The Heritage Foundation's
<I>Index of Economic  Freedom</I>, a global comparison of economic freedom in
142 countries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>End the Castro dictatorship in Cuba.</B> Congress passed and  the
President signed the Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity  Act just a few
days after the February 24, 1996, downing by Cuba  of two U.S. registered
civilian aircraft in international waters.  This legislation, which tightens the
U.S. trade embargo on Cuba  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  allows American citizens to seek
compensation for property  stolen by Castro, is another step toward hastening
the end of  Castro's dictatorship.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reorganize the State Department.</B> Congress proposed to cut  waste in
the State Department and foreign operations accounts by  consolidating several
independent foreign policy agencies into  the State Department. This effort, led
by Senate Foreign  Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms (R-NC), had the
support of  Secretary of State Warren Christopher until bureaucratic  interests
within the Administration persuaded him to oppose it. Key  legislation to move
the Arms Control and Disarmament  Agency (ACDA), United States Information
Agency (USIA), Agency  for International Development (AID), and two other
foreign  policy agencies into the State Department was approved by a 
House-Senate conference committee in March 1996. The President  has vowed to
veto this legislation if approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Express reservations on sending U.S. troops to Bosnia.</B> In  December
1995, the House and Senate passed resolutions to support  the U.S. troops being
deployed on the peacekeeping mission  to Bosnia. These resolutions, however, did
not endorse  the President's decision to deploy them, and raised questions about
 the wisdom of American involvement in a mission lacking clear  goals. The House
went so far as to vote to cut off funds for the  Bosnia mission.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Maintain America's trading relations with China by  approving
most-favored-nation trade status for China.</B> In July 1995, the  Congress
sustained most-favored-nation trading status for China.  This decision reflects
the belief held by a majority in the Congress  that 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  increasing economic interaction
is the best way to promote  economic reform and advance political liberalization
and  human rights.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Protect the U.S. relationship with Taiwan.</B> In the face of 
Administration resistance to granting Taiwan's President Lee Teng-hui  a visa to
visit his alma mater Cornell University, the Congress  voted with near unanimity
in May 1995 to support his visit. As a  result, the President reversed course
and granted the visa. Also, both  the House and Senate, have included provisions
in the 1996 State  Department authorization bill that would give precedence to
the  1979 Taiwan Relations Act over U.S.-China  government-to-government
communiqu&eacute;s when considering future weapons exports to  Taiwan. U.S.
China policy too often is framed by communiqu&eacute;s  that have no force of
law, international or domestic. The Taiwan  Relations Act, however, is the law
of the land. The President  has vowed to veto the bill if approved by Congress.
<P>
