<HEAD>
<TITLE>Public Opinion on U.S. Foreign Policy and Defense -- Issues '96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 20</h3>


<CENTER><H2>PUBLIC OPINION ON U.S. FOREIGN POLICY AND DEFENSE ISSUES
</H2>


<B><CITE>By Brett Schaefer</CITE></B></CENTER>
<P>
<a href="pub_op1.gif">Chart 1</a>: President Clinton's Handling of Foreign Policy<br>
<a href="pub_op2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Who Has A Better Approach to Foreign Policy<br>
<a href="pub_op3.gif">Chart 3</a>: How Much Should U.S. Spend on Defense?<br>
<a href="pub_op4.gif">Chart 4</a>: How Much Should Roregin Aid Be Cut?
<p> 
</P>
<P><B>M</B>ost opinion polls show that Americans are not very interested  in
foreign policy issues. Indeed, a CNN/<I>USA  Today</I>/Gallup poll early in
1996 found that only 14 percent of Americans regard  foreign policy as a top
priority in forming their vote. Nonetheless,  the American people still demand
that America have a strong  foreign policy that fulfills certain expectations.
These expectations  include maintaining America's leadership in the world,
upholding the  respect of other countries for America, and protecting  America's
interests and the country's future. Therefore, even though  Americans may
express little overt interest in specific foreign  issues, they have a latent
expectation that Presidents fulfill certain  expectations. Disappointing these
expectations can prove to be  politically fatal for a President.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The American people are not isolationist; rather they are  largely
indifferent to foreign policy issues, focusing instead on more  immediate
domestic concerns. Isolationism implies America  must intentionally work alone
without allies, without concerning  itself with foreign matters at all.
Isolationism also implies trade  protectionism. Opinion polls show that
Americans are not  isolationist. They still want a strong America, although one
that relates  foreign policy problems to domestic concerns. Americans are 
worried about too much intervention abroad, but they understand the  need 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  for the U.S. to remain engaged in
global affairs. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Since the end of the Gulf War, there has not been a  compelling issue to
ignite the latent interest of Americans in foreign policy.  If there were a
crisis with a clear impact on American security  and vital interests overseas,
foreign policy would return to the top  of political priorities in the polls.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The following are samples of public opinion polling data on  some key
foreign policy questions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Role of the United States in the World</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Please tell me if you agree or disagree with the following  statement: The
U.S. (United States) is playing the role of world  policeman more than it should
be. (Poll taken by the Program on  International Policy Attitudes in <I>Americans
on Defense  Spending</I> on Nov. 18-25, 1995)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Agree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">71%</TD></TR><TR
><TD COLSTART="1">Disagree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">27%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Don't know:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">2%</TD></TR></TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>The U.S. (United States) should play a leading role in dealing  with the
world's problems. (Poll taken by the<I> Times  Mirror</I> on October 25-30,
1995)
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Completely agree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">15%</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Mostly agree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">49%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Mostly disagree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">27%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Completely disagree:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">8%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Don't know:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">1%
</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Bosnia-Herzegovina</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Do you approve or disapprove of President Clinton's decision  to send 20,000
U.S. troops to Bosnia as part of a NATO  peacekeeping force of 60,000 troops to
enforce the peace agreement  reached by the groups who have been fighting there?
 (Poll by  Time/CNN on Dec. 6-7, 1995)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Approve:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">38%</TD></TR><TR
><TD COLSTART="1">Disapprove:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">55%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Not sure:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">7%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>In your view, will the NATO peacekeeping force  which  includes 20,000 U.S.
troops  be successful in establishing a  long-term 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  lasting peace in Bosnia, or don't
you feel that way?  (Poll by  Time/CNN on Dec. 6-7, 1995)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Yes:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">27%</TD></TR><TR>
<TD COLSTART="1">No, don't feel that way:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">60%</TD></TR><TR><TD
 COLSTART="1">Not sure:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">13%
</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Politics of Foreign Policy</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Do you approve or disapprove of the way Bill Clinton is  handling foreign
policy?  (Polls taken on dates noted in graph.  Compilation of NBC News Service/<I>Wall
Street  Journal</I>, CBS News Service/New York Times, and do you think Bill
Clinton has a clear plan for his foreign policy,  or do you think he just reacts
to events as they occur?  (CBS  News poll on June 4-6, 1995)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Clear plan:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">13%</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Reacts to events:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">75%
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Don't know/No answer:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">
12%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P>Who do you think has a better approach to foreign policy,  President
Clinton, Republicans in Congress, or do you think there  isn't much difference
on the issue?  (Poll taken by CBS News  Service on Jan. 2-3, 1996)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Defense Budget and the Size of the Military</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Now I would like you to think about how much the U.S.  should spend on
defenses as compared to its potential enemies.  For discussion's sake, let's
include as potential enemies Russia,  China, North Korea, Iraq, Iran, and Libya.
Here are some possible  levels that have bee suggested for U.S. spending. Please
tell me  which one makes the most sense to you. 1. The U.S. spend a bit  more
than its most powerful enemy. 2. The U.S. should spend about  as much as all of
its potential enemies combined. 3. The U.S.  should spend about twice as much as
all its potential enemies  combined. (Poll by <I>Americans on Defense Spending 
Survey</I> on Nov. 18-25, 1995)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B> Ballistic Missile Defense</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>From what you have heard or read, do you believe there are 
countries  other than Russia  that are getting ballistic missiles  capable of
delivering chemical, biological, or nuclear weapons in  an attack on the United
States or its troops or allies overseas?   (Poll by The Luntz Research Company
on Jan. 2-3, 1995) 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Yes, there are such countries:</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">88%</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">No, there are not such
countries:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">7%</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Don't know:</TD><TD
 COLSTART="2">5%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>How concerned are you that the United States or its forces  and
allies overseas might be attacked by these ballistic Missiles   are you very
concerned, somewhat concerned, not too concerned,  or not concerned at all? 
(Poll by The Luntz Research Company  on Jan. 2-3, 1995) 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Very concerned:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">31%</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Somewhat concerned:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">43%</TD></TR><TR><TD
 COLSTART="1">Not too concerned:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">25%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Don't know/Declined to answer:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">1%</TD></TR></TABLE>
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The truth is some 25 countries  including Iraq, Iran, and 
North Korea  are acquiring ballistic missiles that can be used in an  attack on
the United States or its troops and allies overseas. If one  of these missiles
were fired at the United States today, do you  believe the U.S. military could
destroy the missile before it could hit  and do damage?  (Poll by The Luntz
Research Company on Jan.  2-3, 1995) 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">U.S. military could destroy a ballistic
missile:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">57%
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">U.S. military could not destroy a ballistic
missile:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">29%</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Don't know/No
response:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">14%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The truth is, today the U.S. military cannot protect the 
United States from incoming ballistic missiles. Given this fact, do  you favor
or oppose the deployment of a defense that could  destroy missiles attacking the
United States?  (Poll by The Luntz  Research Company on Jan. 2-3, 1995) 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Favor ballistic missile defense:</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">80%
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Oppose ballistic missile defnse:</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">13%</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Don't know/No response:</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">7%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>[If in favor of deploying a ballistic missile defense] Should 
this deployment be an urgent defense priority or not?  (Poll by  The Luntz
Research Company on Jan. 2-3, 1995) 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Urgent priority:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">67%</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Not urgent:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">27%</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Don't know if it should be a priority:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">6%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Foreign Aid</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In order to balance the budget in 7 years, leaders in Congress 
have proposed a series of cuts in federal spending. Please tell me if  you
approve or disapprove of proposals to cut funding for foreign aid?   (Poll by
Princeton Survey Research Associates on Aug.  17-20, 1995)
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Approve:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">76%</TD></TR><TR
><TD COLSTART="1">Disapprove:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">21%
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Don't know:</TD><TD COLSTART="2">3%
</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P>As you may know, Congress is considering where to cut  government spending
in its new budget. Please tell me if foreign  aid should be cut a great deal, a
fair amount, just a little, or not cut  at all. (Poll by NBC News Service/<I>Wall
Street  Journal</I> on June 2-6, 1995)
</P>
<P></P>
