<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>America's Proper Role in the World - Issues '96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 15</h3>
<center><h2>
AMERICA'S PROPER ROLE IN THE WORLD </H2>
<CITE><B><a href="/heritage/staff/holmes.htm">Kim R. Holmes</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/moore.html">Thomas G. Moore</a> </B></CITE></CENTER>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>M</B>ost Americans believe that America, for all its flaws, is a 
peaceable, generous, and benevolent nation that has been a force  for good in
the world. Today, the industrialized democracies, led  by the United States,
face rising new challenges to their security,  interests, and prosperity. The
fall of the Soviet Union and  Warsaw Pact has meant not the end of threats to
U.S. and allied  security, but the unleashing of forces contained by 45 years of
the  Cold War. U.S. leadership is still vital if America and other free  nations
are to deal effectively with these forces. To provide this  leadership, the
United States needs to remain engaged in world  affairs, working to create
conditions that serve the interests of the U.S.  and its allies and trying to
shape the kind of world in which  democratic institutions, free trade, and the
unimpeded flow of ideas can  flourish.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America cannot be -- nor should it try to be -- the world's  policeman. But
neither can the nation retreat into neo-isolationism.  This is an era
characterized by the global spread of ballistic  missiles; nuclear, chemical,
and biological weapons; and other  high-tech weaponry among potential
adversaries. And while the threat  of thermonuclear war has subsided, at least
from the former  Soviet Union, threats from nuclear proliferation, terrorism,
and tribal  and ethnic conflict have not. Even in this new &quot;Age of Chaos,&quot;
 however, the world remains linked by innumerable strands of  trade, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  commerce, and telecommunications;
and these essential links  must operate despite conflict, confrontation, and
dislocation. A  &quot;Fortress America&quot; strategy in this kind of world is
not workable.  The U.S. could not put its head in the sand for long even if it
wanted  to. The North Koreas, Iraqs, and Irans, not to mention the  positive
demands of trade and commerce, would not allow it.  America needs access to the
world's markets and resources and must  maintain the ability to move goods
freely and safely.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Consequently, acting in concert with friends and allies when  possible but
unilaterally when necessary, the United States should  use all the components of
national power and influence -- diplomacy, trade, communications, and (as a last resort) armed force -- to shape a world friendly to America's interests and
values. In  short, the U.S. needs to make the world safe for America. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>SELECTIVE ENGAGEMENT</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. has global interests and must be a world leader in  ways that suit
its interests, values, and capabilities. Because it is a  trading nation
dedicated to the free exchange of ideas and  goods, America has commercial and
political interests in almost all  corners of the world. Therefore, the U.S.
must be engaged -- through diplomacy, trade, and other means -- in practically all
regions  of the world.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, the U.S. does not have security interests  everywhere. Some of the
world's regions are more important than others.  Since the U.S. cannot be the
world's policeman -- it has neither  the means nor the will to impose a security
order on the world -- it  will have to choose carefully in deciding when, and
under what  cir
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  cumstances, to engage its military
forces and prestige. It will  have to choose strategies, alliances, and military
capabilities that  are best suited to its unique position as the world's only
global  military power. It will have to choose when its use of military force 
is decisive and unique.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To exploit this unique and unenviable position, the U.S.  should adopt a
military strategy of selective engagement  whereby America, lacking a single
global threat, engages its military  power primarily to maintain a balance of
power in regions that are  most vital to her interests. The U.S. must always be
prepared to  protect its borders and regions close to home; for this reason,
security  matters in the Western Hemisphere will always be vitally  important.
But as a global power, the U.S. also must be prepared to  intervene militarily
to maintain a positive balance of power in other key  regions of the world. Now
that the Soviet Union has dissolved,  no single power can challenge the U.S.
globally, but smaller  powers in Europe, Asia, and the Persian Gulf can threaten
U.S.  security interests in these vitally important regions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's &quot;global&quot; strategy is both global and regional. The 
primary aims of U.S. military strategy should be: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>1)</B>  <B>To defend the American people and territory
from attack. </B> Thus, America's top priorities should be not only to deploy a 
ballistic missile defense for the U.S. homeland, but also to take a lead  role
in countering nuclear proliferation and other global threats to  security. <B>
</B>The greatest threat to the peace and stability in the world  today is the
acquisition by rogue regimes or hostile forces of  weapons of mass destruction
(nuclear, biological, and chemical).  The proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction, along with the  ballis
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  tic missiles to deliver them, will
result inevitably in greater  confrontation and conflict unless the free
nations, led by the  United States, take steps to keep dangerous weapons out of
the hands  of potential enemies. America has the resources to counter the 
proliferation of advanced weaponry, including the ability to build  an effective
defense against ballistic missiles, thereby rendering  them less useful.
Harnessing these resources and demonstrating the  leadership necessary to use
them should be a top priority for U.S.  foreign and defense policy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2)  To maintain a balance of power in Europe, Asia, and the
 Persian Gulf.</B> It is still a vital interest of the U.S. to prevent the 
domination of Europe, Asia, or the Persian Gulf by a hostile power  or bloc of
hostile powers. NATO and other military alliances  remain the best ways to
prevent such domination. These alliances are  insurance policies against the
instability and chaos that  brought America into two world wars in this century.
Without an  American military presence in Europe, Asia, and the Persian Gulf,
chaos  and conflict will fill the vacuum if security arrangements among  the
free nations of the world erode. The U.S. must cultivate good  relations with
allies in Europe, Asia, the Middle East, and  Latin America, and where possible
bring emerging democracies  into security partnerships. Top priorities include
bringing new  democracies in Central Europe into NATO and strengthening 
alliances and friendships in Asia.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Therein lies not only the basis of American leadership in the world -- not as the world's policeman, but as the only power capable  of
preventing major regional or even global wars -- but also a  new division of labor
with allies. America's allies should take the  lead in settling purely regional
conflicts, such as the civil war  in 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  Bosnia-Herzogovina, while the U.S.
focuses primarily on the  core military mission of collective defense. The U.S.
should not try  to put out every brushfire that breaks out in Europe or Asia, 
but should husband its resources to deal with larger threats that  endanger the
overall security of these regions. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This strategy of selective engagement is very different from  the one
pursued by the Clinton Administration. The President calls  his strategy &quot;engagement
and enlargement.&quot;  No one is sure  exactly what these terms mean, but his
strategy entails a heavy focus  on peacekeeping, multilateralism, appeasement of
large powers  like Russia and China, and a general neglect of military 
capabilities, military alliances, and the core military missions of those 
alliances.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The strategy of selective engagement is practically the opposite  of
Clinton's approach. Peacekeeping would be downplayed (and  U.S. troop
participation in such operations avoided); multilateralism  de-emphasized except
through military alliances; policies  toward large powers like Russia and China
toughened; military  capabilities maintained at higher levels; and military
alliances focused  on core missions of collective defense, not peacekeeping or 
crisis management. Leadership would be demonstrated not by  engaging in global
social work, as the President has done, but by  emphasizing America's unique and
decisive contributions to world  peace and stability as a global power.


<P>
</P>
<P><B>ECONOMIC PROSPERITY FOR AMERICANS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There is more to maintaining America's leadership role in  the
world than military strategy. There also are the key issues of  trade 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  and economics. To be sure,
America's standard of living  depends on its role as a global power; the wealth
of America as a nation  is inconceivable without the security provided by
America's  armed forces and alliances. But it is also true that America's 
wealth would be inconceivable were it not for its access to overseas  markets
and the relative stability of the world's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For this reason, the U.S. has a vital interest in free trade and  open
overseas markets. As a maritime nation dependent on  foreign trade, the U.S.
depends on access to world markets, raw  materials, and energy resources for its
prosperity and security.  Protecting these interests depends on the free and
safe transit of the air,  space, and the world's sea lanes and maritime choke
points.  Historically, the U.S. has been compelled to intervene with armed force
to  protect these freedoms, and it must remain prepared to do so  when
necessary. But persuasion is always preferable. Therefore, the  U.S. should
conduct an enlightened diplomacy to remove artificial  barriers to the free flow
of goods, services, and ideas,  especially among the industrialized democracies.

<P>
</P>
<P><B>PROMOTING FREEDOM ABROAD</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Americans care deeply about the morality of their foreign 
policy. They wish to see a reflection of themselves as a people in the  foreign
policies which their government pursues. For this reason,  they wish to support
freedom and democracy abroad, not only for  the practical benefits of spreading
peace and stability, but  because doing so is a reflection of their own values
in the world. It also is  a source of inspiration which sustains their
commitments  beyond what is required by self-interest.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, most Americans do not wish to see their country  embark on some
overseas crusade for democracy. They understand  the limits imposed by reality.
It makes little sense to imply, as  the Clinton Administration did in Haiti,
that creating democracy is  a general and unlimited goal of U.S. military
policy. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Nevertheless, it is both a practical and moral benefit for the U.S.  to help
free institutions take root abroad, particularly in  regions where old
totalitarian or authoritarian empires have collapsed.  Free nations grounded in
democratic institutions generally do not  start wars. The freer and more
democratic the world becomes, the  more peaceful, and therefore the more
congenial to U.S. values and  interests, it will be. The best tools with which
to help emerging  democracies are foreign aid and public and private diplomacy, 
not direct military intervention, which should be undertaken  only when vital
interests are threatened.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>CONCLUSION</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These principles can and should guide policymakers, not only 
in the next Administration or next session of Congress, but in  successive
Administrations and Congresses for decades to come. In  short, they should be
viewed as the basic principles of foreign and  defense policy for America in the
21st century. They are, in  essence, the foundations of a post-Cold War national
strategy for the  United States.
</P>
<P><center><B><A HREF="forintro.html">Previous Chapter</A> | <A HREF="chpt16.html">Next Chapter</A> | <A HREF="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</A> | <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a> </B>
</center>



</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
